{"cursor":"56667","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n'Mesopotamia' (from the : \"[land] between rivers\"; (bilÄd al-rÄfidayn); (Beth\nNahrin): \"land of rivers\") is a name for the area of the TigrisâEuphrates river\nsystem, corresponding to modern-day Iraq, the northeastern section of Syria and\nto a lesser extent southeastern Turkey and smaller parts of southwestern Iran.\n\nWidely considered to be the cradle of civilization in the West, Bronze Age\nMesopotamia included Sumer and the Akkadian, Babylonian, and Assyrian empires,\nall native to the territory of modern-day Iraq. In the Iron Age, it was\ncontrolled by the Neo-Assyrian and Neo-Babylonian empires. The indigenous\nSumerians and Akkadians (including Assyrians and Babylonians) dominated\nMesopotamia from the beginning of written history (c. 3100 BC) to the fall of\nBabylon in 539 BC, when it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire. It fell to\nAlexander the Great in 332 BC, and after his death, it became part of the Greek\nSeleucid Empire.\n\nAround 150 BC, Mesopotamia was under the control of the Parthians. Mesopotamia\nbecame a battleground between the Romans and Parthians, with parts of\nMesopotamia coming under ephemeral Roman control. In AD 226, it fell to the\nSassanid Persians and remained under Persian rule until the 7th century Arab\nIslamic conquest of the Sassanid Empire. A number of primarily neo Assyrian and\nChristian native Mesopotamian states existed between the 1st century BC and 3rd\ncentury AD, including Adiabene, Osroene, and Hatra.\n","linknr":1120,"url":"Mesopotamia","recorded":1362503420,"links":137,"instances":["temple","goddess","agriculture","angle","business","persian_province","mythology","gods","mythology","systems_theory","roman_province","roman_province","pharmaceutical","club","burial","syria","pharmacy"],"pdf":["http://oi.uchicago.edu/pdf/OIS2.pdf","http://fax.libs.uga.edu/DS49x2xM465D/1f/dweller_in_mesopotamia.pdf","http://fax.libs.uga.edu/DS69x5x